<br>
I would have liked to have seen the beginning of this thread when I first posted information in this dialog, so that I would have known who was contributing.  For the benefit of new readers, <br><br>
My name is Cook Barela; I was 18 years old when I went to Vietnam. I was in the United States Marine Corps, volunteered for duty. I served with 1st platoon, India company 3rd Battalion 7th Marines, 1st Marine Division, June 1967-July 1968. I was a machine gunner and kept a diary in Vietnam that I have now rewritten into book form and I am in the process of editing.<br><br>
Most of the mass demonstrations, drugs and discipline problems were unknown when I fought against communist aggression in South East Asia. <br>
I went there in answered to my country's call to battle. When I returned stateside, I found it a different world, and remained silent for over 30 years. History's shame denied me the right to share the fields of fire and the honor and glory I witnessed in Vietnam. <br><br>
Because of my active duty in the Republic of Vietnam I received, the following recognition.<br>
The Combat Action Ribbon; The Presidential Unit Citation with two Bronze stars, Meritorious unit Citation, Good Conduct Medal, National Defense Service Medal, Vietnam Service Medal w/three bronze stars, Republic of Vietnam Meritorious Unit Citation (Gallantry Cross Color),<br>
Republic of Vietnam Meritorious Unit Citation (Civil Actions Color, 1st Class), <br>
Republic of Vietnam Campaign Medal, and other military decorations.<br>
I was proud to serve and to receive those medals not because I earned them, but because of the Marines that died or were seriously wounded alongside of me. <br>
On November 21, 1967, 40 of us in 1st platoon were attacked by a reinforced company of Communist regulars North Vietnamese soldiers (about 380 of them). Only 12 of us came out of that firefight without getting killed or wounded. During the battle, a grenade thrown by the enemy blew me back, but it was my A-gunner that received most of the fragmentation. <br>
The next day when the brass came out awarding purple hearts, I was sitting on the rice paddy dike where two Marines had died and others had been wounded the day before, their blood was still visible on the ground. I reached up and took my yellow medivac tag that revealed I had been wounded and buried it in the mud, got up and moved out. <br>
It is in honor of those men who were killed or wounded, in battle who believed in our country that I have chosen to contribute to this dialog.<br><br>
I am Cook Barela and those are my thoughts and who I am.<br>

